[5] Wisconsin
Date: 8 Oct 2020
Source: The Horse [edited]
https://thehorse.com/193143/four-wisconsin-horses-succumb-to-eee/


Officials at the Wisconsin Department of Agriculture, Trade and Consumer Protection (WDATCP) have confirmed 4 horses with EEE: 2 in Taylor County and one each in Sheboygan and Lincoln counties. All 4 horses were unvaccinated.

The Taylor County horses were confirmed positive on 17 Sep 2020. The 1st, a 9 year old pony mare, experienced onset of clinical signs on 10 Sep 2020. Signs included ataxia (loss of muscle control), depression, disorientation, shallow respiration, minimal reflexes, recumbency (down and unable to rise), and near-coma condition. The 2nd, a 10 year old paint mare, experienced ataxia and depression progressing to recumbency beginning 11 Sep 2020. The pony mare died, and the paint mare was euthanized. The cases brought Taylor County's tally of confirmed equine cases to 3.

On 17 Sep 2020, 2 additional horses, one in Sheboygan County and one in Lincoln County, began showing signs.

The Sheboygan County horse, a 7 year old quarter horse gelding, exhibited fever and began circling, lost muscle control, experienced difficulty swallowing (dysphagia), and leaned against objects, progressing to recumbency. He was confirmed positive on 25 Sep 2020 and was euthanized. He was Sheboygan County's 1st confirmed equine case for 2020.

The Lincoln County horse, a 9 year old quarter horse gelding, began showing signs consisting of fever, acute-onset depression, anorexia, ataxia, and recumbency. He was also confirmed positive on 25 Sep 2020 and euthanized. This was Lincoln County's 1st confirmed case this year [2020].

The cases bring Wisconsin's confirmed equine cases this year [2020] to 20.

[byline: Diane E Rice]

